paper-book","sectionId":"news","sectionName":"News","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/mainsection","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/mainsection","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"publication/theguardian","webTitle":"The Guardian","type":"publication","sectionId":"theguardian","sectionName":"From the Guardian","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/all","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/publication/theguardian","references":[]}],"references":[],"elements":[]},{"webTitle":"Kenya attack: a photographer's view from the Westgate mall","webPublicationDate":"2013-09-25T12:20:12Z","sectionName":"Art and design","sectionId":"artanddesign","id":"artanddesign/photography-blog/2013/sep/25/kenya-attack-photographers-westgate-mall","fields":{"secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/25/1380108975483/Women-carrying-children-r-004.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3j3bj","standfirst":"Goran Tomasevic is Reuters chief photographer for East Africa, based in Nairobi, Kenya.  He recounts his experiences covering the first few hours of the attack by Islamist militants on the Westgate shopping mall. <strong>WARNING: The images following are graphic and may cause distress to some readers</strong>","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-06-20T09:41:04Z","body":"<p>I was at home when I heard from a friend about something happening but we weren't sure what it was so I went to the Westgate mall and saw some bodies lying in the car park and realised it was serious. I saw some police so I hid behind cars to take cover and slowly got closer to the gate. An injured child was being pushed in a supermarket trolley, a woman asked me to take the child but the police jumped in and helped her. I took some pictures and then saw a couple of plainclothes and uniformed police officers, I asked when they would be moving and they said they were going to try and enter the shopping mall from the top. I went with them.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-418239297'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/25/1380108466728/-injured-child-in-a-shopp-006.jpg' alt=' injured child in a shopping trolley during the attack on the Westgate shopping centre ' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Security forces push an injured child in a shopping trolley past the body of a victim of the attack. Photograph: Goran Tomasevic/Reuters</figcaption></figure><p>In the parking lot there were a many dead bodies, injured people and blood everywhere. There were people hiding and screaming and asking for help, I tried to help but I couldn't do much because the ambulance was arriving and I wasn't sure exactly what to do. I saw a young guy who was hit by shrapnel, his leg was broken but he wasn't bleeding that heavily, I didn't want to move him and make it worse. I was worried that  if I started helping I would do something wrong, I am not a doctor, I just tried to calm him down and said \"The medics are coming. You will be alright. You are okay.\"</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-418239298'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/25/1380107274638/A-wounded-man-sits-in-the-009.jpg' alt='A wounded man sits in the car park of the Westgate Shopping Centre' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>A wounded man sits in the car park of the Westgate shopping mall. Photograph: Goran Tomasevic/Reuters</figcaption></figure><p>I entered the mall and followed the police searching room by room until we ended up on the ground floor where the supermarket is located. A policeman was shot in the stomach, he asked me to take a picture of him and asked me for help. I tried to help him but he must have been in shock, when I helped him up he started firing his rifle into the floor, almost shooting me accidentally, then dropped his weapon.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-418239299'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/25/1380107780864/An-injured-police-officer-009.jpg' alt='An injured police officer hold his wound during the attack on the Westgate shopping mall' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>An injured police officer hold his gunshot wound during the attack. Photograph: Goran Tomasevic/Reuters</figcaption></figure><p>At one point I was hiding with some police officers behind a column, a kind of stand holding something up. It wasn't part of the building, I knocked on it and found it was made out of thin material. I said \"Hey guys knock on this!\", everyone started to knock, they said \"So, what?\". I said \"It's not going to protect us\" so, I dived down and everyone followed suit.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-418239300'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/25/1380107983212/Soldiers-and-armed-police-006.jpg' alt='Soldiers and armed police take cover during the attack on the Westgate shopping mall' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Soldiers and armed police take cover. Photograph: Goran Tomasevic/Reuters</figcaption></figure><p>A woman ran out from a shop with some children and I helped them to get out, I took one of their hands and helped them to keep together. People were panicking, they were all in total shock; they didn't know what was going on. </p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-418239301'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/25/1380107040760/A-soldier-carries-a-child-009.jpg' alt='A soldier carries a child to safety at the Westgate shopping centre in Nairobi' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>A soldier carries a child to safety. Photograph: Goran Tomasevic/Reuters</figcaption></figure><p>I helped the police with some of the evacuations but after some time they asked me to leave and I decided it was time to do that, I was inside for around 4-5 hours. It wasn't possible to get close to the mall the following day, the police dropped a tear gas canister on journalists. I was trying to think of how to get back into the mall but I din't believe I could get in without being arrested as I was carrying my 500mm lens. You have to feel the atmosphere, know when a good time is, if you miss your opportunity, you cannot go ahead, you have to feel it and react quickly.</p><p>The attack was a complex situation, my experience in conflict zones helps to recognise where potential threats are and what is going on. I've seen a lot of different situations of people dying but I always say it's my job to cover these stories and if I can help someone, I will. I always believe people should see how it is and sometimes it's terrible but they should know the reality.</p><p>• <em>This is an edited version of a blogpost which first appeared on the Reuters <a href=\"http://blogs.reuters.com/photographers-blog/\">Photographers Blog</a></em></p>","headline":"Kenya attack: a photographer's view from the Westgate mall","trailText":"<p>Goran Tomasevic of Reuters recounts his experiences covering the first few hours of the attack by Islamist militants on the Westgate shopping mall</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/25/1380108975483/Women-carrying-children-r-004.jpg","wordcount":"634","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"418236321","allowUgc":"false","isPremoderated":"false","internalPageCode":"1970803","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2013-10-02T12:20:12Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/photography-blog/2013/sep/25/kenya-attack-photographers-westgate-mall","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.