 so-called Generation 1.5, those who weren&rsquo;t born in Norway but came when they were quite young, falling between two cultures,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;[Al-Shabaab] need people who are quite ignorant about Somalia. That is in their interest because that will give them a more internationalist agenda. And it might also make them more dangerous when they return back to their home countries.&rdquo;</p> <p>Last week Norway&rsquo;s intelligence agency, the PST, said it was <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/11/world/africa/norway-kenya-mall-siege.html\">attempting to verify reports</a> that a Norwegian citizen had been involved in the assault on the shopping centre, which lasted four days.</p> <p>&ldquo;We have lately seen an increase in the number of persons leaving Norway to take part in acts of war, attend training camps or join terrorist networks abroad,&rdquo; the Norwegian authorities said. &ldquo;We are concerned that this development may have an increasingly negative impact on the threat situation in Norway.&rdquo;</p> <p>A Kenyan al-Shabaab leader whom US commandos targeted in a raid in Somalia on 5 October, but failed to capture, reportedly may have spent time in Norway, according to the Norwegian station TV2. It said <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/07/us-navy-raid-somalia-target\">Abdukadir Mohamed Abdukadir</a>, also known as Ikrima, had travelled to Norway and applied for asylum in 2004 but left in 2008 before receiving a decision on his application. Norwegian officials have not commented on the claims.</p>","headline":"Westgate mall suspect identified by BBC as Norwegian national","trailText":"Relative says 23-year-old left Larvik for Somalia in 2009 and told his family in his last phone call home that he was in trouble","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3jk38","wordcount":"480","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"420321309","allowUgc":"